African leaders that are ousted from positions of power.
Earlier this week, Mali's military staged a coup in which they ousted President Ibrahim Boubacar Keita.
Keita is the 15th president to be forced out of power in Africa in the last 10 years.
On February 18, 2010, the military in the Republic of Niger ousted President Mamadou Tandja after he amended the country's constitution to allow him a third term.
On January 14, 2011, a revolution overthrew the government of Prime Minister Zine El Abidine Ben Ali, who fled the country after 23 years in power.
On February 11, 2011, protests forced Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak to step down after 30 years in power, allowing the military to take over the government.
On April 11, 2011, security forces arrested Cote d'Ivoire's President Laurent Gbagbo in the aftermath of violence following the election in which Alasassne Ouattara was declared the winner.
On October 20, 2011, Libyan leader Moammar Ghadafi, who had been in power for nearly 42 years, was assassinated by Libyan rebels with the help of NATO forces.
On March 22, 2012, the military in Mali rebelled and arrested President Amadou Toumane Toure.
On April 12, 2012, Guinea-Bissau President Raimundo Pereira and former Prime Minister Carlos Gomes Junior were arrested by the military in connection with a disputed presidential election.
On March 24, 2013, the rebel group Seleka forced President Francois Bozize to step down, appointing their leader Michel Djotodia to rule, but he also resigned on January 10, 2014. due to international pressure.
On October 31, 2014, the military forced President Blaise Compaore, who had spent 27 years in power, to flee the country, but less than a year later his successor, interim President Michel Kafando, was also forced to step down, however he was later restored.
On January 21, 2017, Yahya Jammeh left The Gambia after losing the presidential election to Adama Barrow.
On November 21, 2017, Zimbabwe's President Robert Mugabe, who had ruled the country for 37 years, resigned from his position after parliament began debating his impeachment, and while his former deputy, Emmerson Mnangagwa succeeded him.
On February 14, 2018, South African President Jacob Zuma stepped down from power following an attempt to oust him over allegations of bribery and corruption, allowing his deputy and ANC party leader Cyril Ramaphosa the chance to be the president.
On April 2, 2019, Algerian President Abdelaziz Bouteflika, who had been in power for 20 years, resigned from his position following protests over the cost of living and his demand for a fifth term.
On April 11 this year, the military overthrew the government of Sudanese President Omar Hassan al-Bashir in the wake of four months of protests in the country, a step which paved the way for the formation of an interim government consisting of both military and civilians.
